{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01SWZ6F3avK3cHmtAxkYpKYm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Dockerfile starts from `cloche-base:latest` which likely has the `cloche` and `cloche-agent` binaries. But I'm not 100% sure. However, `cloche get`/`cloche set` work purely with local files - they don't need a daemon connection.\n\nFor the container workflow (`develop.cloche`), the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` is set via the docker runtime (line 49 of runtime.go). But the agent unsets it (line 33 of main.go) - `os.Unsetenv(\"CLOCHE_RUN_ID\")`. So inside the container, after the agent starts, `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` is no longer in the environment.\n\n\nThis creates a problem: `cloche get/set` commands inside the container can't access the run ID since it's been removed from the environment, and the agent keeps it stored in `RunnerConfig.RunID` without passing it down to child processes. I need to check whether the generic adapter handles this when executing script steps inside the container.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":472,"cache_read_input_tokens":61923,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":472},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5096be8a-dfc2-4986-a448-2dc8a604d8e8","uuid":"2ec3d6c0-5bcc-45bb-898f-7510d37d6c74"}
